bash$ insmod litmus_scheduler.ko device=/dev/thermo0
$ echo 'litmus' > /sys/kernel/sched/policy model ProcessScheduler {
    // Learn each process's characteristics
    cpu_demand[N] ~ Exponential(1.0)
    io_wait[N] ~ Exponential(0.5)
    priority[N] ~ Normal(5.0, 2.0)
    
    // Make scheduling decisions
    core_assignment[N] ~ Categorical(uniform)
    time_slice[N] ~ Categorical([5ms, 10ms, 20ms, 50ms])
    
    // Physics-based constraints
    factor load_balance { ... }
    factor cache_affinity { ... }
    factor priority_satisfaction { ... }
}
```

## Why This is Revolutionary

**Traditional schedulers:**
- Hand-coded heuristics (nice values, load balancing rules)
- Fixed policies (round-robin, priority queues)
- Can't adapt to workload changes

**Litmus scheduler:**
- **Learns process behavior** from observations
- **Optimizes globally** across all constraints simultaneously
- **Adapts in real-time** — updates every 100ms
- **Runs on thermodynamic chip** — 5ms compute budget for 1000 processes

## The Energy Function

All these competing goals become **one physics equation:**
```
Energy = load_imbalance²
       + cache_migrations × memory_footprint
       + (priority - time_slice)²
       + memory_contention²
